John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland have traditionally provided excellent education. Looking at the latest outstanding exam results, this situation has not changed by 2018, which is further reinforced by individual and group successes in sports, arts, music and other community initiatives.
In Scotland, more than 30,000 students are already studying at institutions of this kind, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), which strive to provide the best possible service to students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare students for further education, higher education, their chosen careers, and the positions they occupy as citizens of the world.
In an educational sector where it is possible to design and introduce customized school curricula, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and sought-after subjects.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to someone in a language that they understand, they get to their head.
But if you speak in his language, it will reach his heart.”
This is an important reminder, because we cannot rely solely on English to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s exam results, we can see that students from independent schools across the country have the best results from foreign languages.
Sixty-eight percent of all students studying a foreign language achieved a higher A grade (over eighty-five percent).
Data from 74 SCIS member schools shows that 72 percent of students received higher A grades in Mandarin, while 72 percent of German students, 69 percent of French students and 63 percent of Spanish students achieved A grades.
These findings also show that independent schools in Scotland see foreign languages as essential knowledge that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages have become as important as natural sciences, technology, engineering and mathematics, both in independent and non-independent schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Employment and Vocational Training Commission showed that 17% of employers found it difficult to fill vacancies because of a lack of language skills.
This shows that language skills are becoming increasingly necessary for young people to have a successful career.
As knowledge of foreign languages is expected in more and more workplaces, language skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career you choose, if you have learned a foreign language, you will gain lifelong knowledge that will bring you a clear benefit.
The ability to communicate directly with people of other nationalities automatically gives a competitive advantage to a candidate who speaks several languages.
According to a YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75 percent of respondents did not speak a single foreign language well enough to communicate with others, and French was the only language spoken by more than 10 percent (15 percent) of respondents.
This is why it is important to focus on language education for children.
Speaking more languages, especially those of developing countries, can be a tool in the hands of children, equipping them to apply for more important jobs as adults.
Every school in Scotland will have different languages.
Many schools will focus on classical modern languages, while others will teach languages such as Mandarin or Japanese, which are expected to be of paramount importance for the UK by 2020.
Whatever your child’s area of interest, you will be able to learn a number of optional languages at independent schools and will be trained by educators who are experts in their field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment for children that equips and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
It is not difficult to notice that in the current global business environment, languages remain vital for the future of a country, and this should be reflected in education.
As a matter of fact, knowledge of modern languages should rather be treated as "international communication skills".
Independent schools offer choice, diverse and quality education to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire – that’s how it should be.
John Edward, President of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
