Harvard students are taught to have enough rest
A new subject at Harvard University this year prompted students to sleep more, fighting against the increasingly macho culture of caffeine-heated night-long learning.
One academic concluded that students at the world’s number one university are often completely lost when it comes to how they should take care of themselves.
The course, the first of its kind in the United States, was designed by Professor Charles Czeisler, who teaches sleep medicine at Harvard College of Medicine and practises as a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital.
He was encouraged to develop the course by giving a lecture earlier on the effect of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came up to me and asked me, ‘Why do I face this now as a senior?’
He said that no one ever told him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me," he told the Telegraph.
The course, launched for the first time this year, teaches students how proper sleep patterns have a fundamental impact on their academic and sporting performance, in addition to having a positive impact on their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard College of Medicine and director of the university’s health service, said the university decided to start the course because during the week, students were found to be extremely sleepy.
The one-hour course also includes a series of interactive exercises.
In one, for example, they show a picture of a dorm room where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to get acquainted with the effects of caffeine and light, how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and why bedtime routines are important.
Another section explains how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
They present a map of the university area with interactive icons to encourage participants to rethink their daily routine.
“We know that we are not going to change the behavior of students immediately.
But we think they have a right to this knowledge – just as they have a right to be aware of the health effects of smoking,” Czeisler said.
A culture that continues to flourish in which it is an achievement to study through a night or two, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students result in increasing problems of insomnia.
Sufficient and quality sleep is a student’s “secret weapon” in the fight against stress, exhaustion, and anxiety, and even protects against obesity, as sleep deprivation forces the brain into a starving mode and causes a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So helped Professor Czeisler set up the course, a 19-year-old Californian student studying chemistry and biophysics, and last year at Harvard, he took one of the professor’s courses as a freshman.
He said that what he heard there opened his eyes and encouraged him to start a university-level training.
It hopes that, as a next step, postgraduate students will be able to participate in a similar degree programme before entering the competitive sector.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set a warning to go to bed, a wake-up call, and get acquainted with the damaging effects of “blue light” emitted by electric screens and LED light sources, which could easily distract them from their daily rhythms and make it difficult to fall asleep.
