The National Trust is investigating the secret life of bats.
New research is being carried out on a Scottish Highlands estate to find out how bats exploit the landscape features during hunting.
The researchers hope that the findings will provide new information on the behavior of unique flying mammals, which may be useful for future species conservation initiatives.
Scientists from the National Trust for Scotland will study the behavior of common and soprano dwarf bats, as well as brown long-eared bats and water bats in the Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
At the appropriate points of the area, special recording devices are placed to record the activities of bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will use handheld detectors to collect mobile data.
By analyzing the sound of the recordings in detail, you can determine the frequency of bat sounds and what species are doing.
The researchers will also create a habitat map and report that will help to determine in detail how the behaviour of the animals will evolve depending on the landscape.
NTS conservation adviser Rob Dewar hopes the results will reveal what are the most important habitats for bats and how they are used by species.
This information helps to determine the beneficial effects of habitat management work, such as meadows, and how best to preserve forested areas for bats and other affected species.
The size of bat populations in Scotland and the United Kingdom has decreased significantly over the past century.
Construction and spatial development work disrupt the sleeping areas of animals and reduce their living space.
Wind turbines and public lighting are also a risk factor for them, just as they are exposed to fly paper, certain chemical processes used in building materials, and attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not completely blind.
However, because they are nocturnal predators, they rely more on their hearing than on their sight when hunting prey.
With their sophisticated technique based on ultrasound reflection, they are able to determine the exact location of insects and the landmarks in their path.
NTS, which is responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes bats very seriously.
They work with ten trained specialists who regularly conduct studies and sleep site inspections and occasionally participate in rescue work.
The organization established Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve in the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
According to manager David Thompson, the area is an ideal habitat for bats.
“There’s a great place for bats in Threave,” he said.
“There are old buildings, lots of old trees, and everything else that is needed for a good living space.
But there’s a lot we don’t know about bats, and thanks to working here and in other areas like this, we can learn more about what they need to feel great.”
He also highlighted the importance of making sure that bats are present before renovating the buildings, as the destruction of a single plant could result in the death of 400 females and young individuals, which could lead to the extinction of the entire local population.
Bats are protected animals and their destruction, harassment and habitat disturbance are prohibited by law.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish representative of the Bat Conservation Trust, also asked for help from the public.
"There is still much that we don't know about bats, and we have almost no information about the population status of most domestic species."
